Tom, I have just realized that I completely misunderstood this. Now I can see that {{participants}} is inside every {{reviewItem}} and not shared (and single) for the whole review. Now everything makes sense. Please then treat my former comments loosely as they may be bullshit.
Now a few questions: - does {{participants}} refer to parent {{reviewItem}} only or can we track this info per {{versionedLineCommentData}} too? - does Crucible want to serve this info (so precisely) to other people? I.e. do you want other review participants to see which concrete FRXes were read (completed) by selected reviewer? - do we really need {{author}} and {{moderator}} flags in {{participant}}? IMO {{username}} and {{completed}} flag itself would be sufficient. When you read review details, you already know the moderator and the author, so you can map concrete participants to concrete roles on the client side. IMO API would be cleaner then and less redundant. E.g. {noformat}
<participants> .. <participant> <userName>nick</userName> <completed>false</ </participant> ... <participants> {noformat} - I understand that all this information can be used to render review completion progress bars (by counting FRX-es with {{completed}} = true divided by all FRX-es) for all review participants. As I said it would be good to achieve something similar on the client side, but I just wonder if it wouldn't be sufficient if Crucible serves me just this percentage (for all participants on the shared/root level of review details)? I have nothing against having the access to all this data, but it means that now reviewers using non-web UI clients could actually see much more (do we want it?) about the progress of other reviewers than in Crucible itself. Am I right? Or perhaps Crucible shows such data in web UI even now and I just don't know where and how to get it?

